SIMPLE: oyer
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Oyer
<hw>O"yer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Anglo F., a hearing,
from OF. <ets>o⟦ium⟧r</ets>, F. <ets>ou⟦ium⟧r</ets>, to hear, L.
<ets>audire</ets>. See <er>Audible</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A
hearing or an inspection, as of a deed, bond, etc., <as>as when a
defendant in court prays <ex>oyer</ex> of a writing</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Oyer and terminer</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a term
used in England in commissions directed to judges of assize about to
hold court, directing them to hear and determine cases brought before
them. In the U.S. the phrase is used to designate certain criminal
courts.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oyez</ent>⟦br⟧
